This article delves into the mathematical concept of [integers](/Integer), a foundational set of [numbers](/Number). For a discussion of integers as a specific [data type](/Data_type) within computing contexts, please refer to the article on [Integer (computer science)](/Integer_(computer_science)).

The integers, when meticulously arranged upon a [number line](/Number_line), reveal a perfectly ordered, infinitely extending sequence.

An integer, at its core, is a [number](/Number) that possesses no [fractional component](/Fraction). It can be the solitary [zero](/0), any positive [natural number](/Natural_number) (such as 1, 2, 3, and so forth, extending indefinitely), or the precise negation of a positive natural number ([−1](/%E2%88%921), −2, −3, and so on). The negations, or more formally, the [additive inverses](/Additive_inverse), of these positive [natural numbers](/Natural_number) are distinctly recognized as negative integers. The complete [set](/Set_(mathematics)) encompassing all integers is routinely symbolized in [boldface](/Boldface) as Z or, more commonly and elegantly in mathematical texts, as [blackboard bold](/Blackboard_bold)




Z



{\displaystyle \mathbb {Z} }

.

The [set](/Set_(mathematics)) of [natural numbers](/Natural_number), typically denoted as




N



{\displaystyle \mathbb {N} }

, is, rather predictably, a [subset](/Subset) of this broader collection,




Z



{\displaystyle \mathbb {Z} }

. This set of integers, in turn, forms a [subset](/Subset) of the [rational numbers](/Rational_number), denoted as




Q



{\displaystyle \mathbb {Q} }

, which itself is a [subset](/Subset) of the [real numbers](/Real_number) &#8288;




R



{\displaystyle \mathbb {R} }

&#8288;. To be more precise, each of these number systems is [embedded](/Embedding) into the subsequent one, meaning there's an [isomorphic mapping](/Isomorphism) of the initial set to a [subset](/Subset) of the next. For those who prefer a more streamlined, if less constructive, view, one might define the [real numbers](/Real_number) first and then consider the other sets as mere [subsets](/Subset) within that grand continuum.

Much like its progenitor, the set of [natural numbers](/Natural_number), the collection of integers,




Z



{\displaystyle \mathbb {Z} }

, possesses the property of being [countably infinite](/Countable_set). This means, despite its boundless extent, its elements can be put into a one-to-one correspondence with the [natural numbers](/Natural_number). Fundamentally, an integer can be conceived as a [real number](/Real_number) that conveniently presents itself without any cumbersome [fractional component](/Fraction). To illustrate, numbers like 21, 4, [0](/0), and −2048 are undeniably integers. However, 9.75, &#8288;5+1/2&#8288;, 5/4, and the enigmatic [square root of 2](/Square_root_of_2) decidedly are not. These are the numbers that, for better or worse, maintain their 'wholeness'.

The integers hold a rather significant position in [algebraic structure](/Algebraic_structure). They constitute the smallest possible [group](/Group_(mathematics)) and the smallest possible [ring](/Ring_(mathematics)) that contain the [natural numbers](/Natural_number). This is not a trivial observation; it underscores their fundamental role. Within the sophisticated realm of [algebraic number theory](/Algebraic_number_theory), these straightforward integers are sometimes given the slightly more specific designation of *rational integers*. This is done to prevent confusion, distinguishing them from the broader, more abstract category of [algebraic integers](/Algebraic_integer). Indeed, (rational) integers are precisely those [algebraic integers](/Algebraic_integer) that also happen to be [rational numbers](/Rational_number)—a neat little intersection, for those who appreciate such things.

## History

The very word "integer" has its roots in the ancient [Latin](/Latin) term *integer*, which translates to "whole" or, quite literally, "untouched." It stems from the prefix *in-* ("not") combined with *tangere* ("to touch"). The English word "entire" also traces its lineage back to this same origin, having passed through the [French language](/French_language) word *entier*, which, rather conveniently, means both "entire" and "integer."

Historically, the term "integer" was initially applied to any [number](/Number) that was a direct multiple of 1, or, alternatively, to the whole portion of a [mixed number](/Mixed_number). In those early days, the mathematical community primarily concerned itself with positive integers, rendering the term effectively synonymous with the [natural numbers](/Natural_number). It took a considerable amount of time, and perhaps a fair bit of philosophical hand-wringing, for the definition of "integer" to expand and embrace [negative numbers](/Negative_number), as their practical utility and conceptual necessity gradually became undeniable. For instance, the formidable [Leonhard Euler](/Leonhard_Euler), in his seminal 1765 work, *[Elements of Algebra](/Elements_of_Algebra)*, explicitly defined integers to include both their positive and negative counterparts, marking a significant shift in mathematical thought. One might wonder what took them so long to grasp the concept of 'less than nothing.'

The precise phrase "the set of the integers" only began to see widespread use towards the close of the 19th century. This timing is no mere coincidence, as it aligns directly with the period when [Georg Cantor](/Georg_Cantor) pioneered the revolutionary concepts of [infinite sets](/Infinite_set) and [set theory](/Set_theory), forever altering the landscape of mathematics. The adoption of the letter Z to symbolically represent the set of integers is derived from the [German language](/German_language) word *Zahlen*, meaning "numbers." This particular notation is widely credited to the influential mathematician [David Hilbert](/David_Hilbert). The earliest documented appearance of this notation in a published textbook can be found in *[Algèbre](/%C3%89l%C3%A9ments_de_math%C3%A9matique)*, a work produced by the collective known as [Nicolas Bourbaki](/Nicolas_Bourbaki), dating back to 1947.

However, the notation wasn't universally adopted overnight. For a period, some textbooks opted for alternative symbols, such as the letter J. As late as 1960, a notable academic paper utilized Z to specifically denote the non-negative integers, demonstrating the lack of a unified standard. Yet, by 1961, the symbol Z had largely become the standard and generally accepted notation within modern algebra texts for representing the complete set of positive and negative integers. It seems even mathematicians, eventually, can agree on *some* things.

