Much like their simpler cousins, the [natural numbers](/Natural_numbers), the set &#8288;




Z



{\displaystyle \mathbb {Z} }

&#8288; exhibits [closure](/Closure_(mathematics)) under the fundamental [operations](/Binary_operation) of addition and [multiplication](/Multiplication). This simply means that if you take any two integers and add them together, or multiply them, the result will, predictably, also be an integer. Anything less would be chaos, wouldn't it? However, the inclusion of the negative [natural numbers](/Natural_number) (and, critically, [0](/0_(number))) bestows upon &#8288;




Z



{\displaystyle \mathbb {Z} }

&#8288; a significant advantage over the [natural numbers](/Natural_number): it is also [closed](/Closure_(mathematics)) under [subtraction](/Subtraction). This seemingly minor addition introduces a whole new level of algebraic utility.

The integers, as a collective, form a [ring](/Ring_(mathematics)), which can be considered the most fundamental of its kind. This isn't just a casual observation; it's a profound statement about its structure. In essence, for any given [ring](/Ring_(mathematics)) in the mathematical universe, there exists a single, unique [ring homomorphism](/Ring_homomorphism) that maps from the integers into that specific [ring](/Ring_(mathematics)). This [universal property](/Universal_property), the distinction of being an [initial object](/Initial_object) within the entire [category of rings](/Category_of_rings), uniquely defines the ring &#8288;




Z



{\displaystyle \mathbb {Z} }

&#8288;. This singular homomorphism is [injective](/Injective) if and only if the [characteristic](/Characteristic_(algebra)) of the target [ring](/Ring_(mathematics)) is zero. A direct consequence of this is that any [ring](/Ring_(mathematics)) possessing a characteristic of zero must, by definition, contain a [subring](/Subring) that is [isomorphic](/Isomorphism) to &#8288;




Z



{\displaystyle \mathbb {Z} }

&#8288;, and this [subring](/Subring) will always be its smallest. It's the ultimate foundation, in a sense.

However, &#8288;




Z



{\displaystyle \mathbb {Z} }

&#8288; is conspicuously *not* [closed](/Closure_(mathematics)) under [division](/Division_(mathematics)). The quotient of two integers (for example, 1 divided by 2) is, more often than not, not an integer itself. Expecting a tidy result every time is simply naive. Furthermore, while the [natural numbers](/Natural_number) are [closed](/Closure_(mathematics)) under [exponentiation](/Exponentiation) (positive integer powers of natural numbers yield natural numbers), the integers are not. This is because negative exponents would inevitably lead to fractions, pulling the result outside the integer set.

The following table, if you can bear to look at it, outlines some of the fundamental properties governing addition and multiplication for any arbitrary integers *a*, *b*, and *c*:

| Properties of addition and multiplication on integers | Addition                                | Multiplication                                    |
| :---------------------------------------------------- | :-------------------------------------- | :------------------------------------------------ |
| [Closure](/Closure_(mathematics)):                    | *a* + *b* is an integer                 | *a* × *b* is an integer                           |
| [Associativity](/Associativity):                      | *a* + (*b* + *c*) = (*a* + *b*) + *c*   | *a* × (*b* × *c*) = (*a* × *b*) × *c*             |
| [Commutativity](/Commutativity):                      | *a* + *b* = *b* + *a*                   | *a* × *b* = *b* × *a*                             |
| Existence of an [identity element](/Identity_element): | *a* + 0 = *a*                           | *a* × 1 = *a*                                     |
| Existence of [inverse elements](/Inverse_element):    | *a* + (−*a*) = 0                        | The only invertible integers (called [units](/Unit_(ring_theory))) are −1 and 1. |
| [Distributivity](/Distributivity):                    |                                         | *a* × (*b* + *c*) = (*a* × *b*) + (*a* × *c*) and (*a* + *b*) × *c* = (*a* × *c*) + (*b* × *c*) |
| No [zero divisors](/Zero_divisor):                    |                                         | If *a* × *b* = 0, then *a* = 0 or *b* = 0 (or both) |

The first five properties articulated above, specifically concerning addition, collectively demonstrate that &#8288;




Z



{\displaystyle \mathbb {Z} }

&#8288;, when considered under the operation of addition, forms an [abelian group](/Abelian_group). Furthermore, it is also a [cyclic group](/Cyclic_group), a rather elegant characteristic, as every non-zero integer can be expressed as a finite sum of either 1 + 1 + ... + 1 or (−1) + (−1) + ... + (−1). In fact, &#8288;




Z



{\displaystyle \mathbb {Z} }

&#8288; under addition holds the unique distinction of being the *only* infinite [cyclic group](/Cyclic_group)—meaning any other infinite [cyclic group](/Cyclic_group) is structurally [isomorphic](/Group_isomorphism) to &#8288;




Z



{\displaystyle \mathbb {Z} }

&#8288;. A certain kind of fundamental elegance, wouldn't you say?

Conversely, the initial four properties enumerated above for multiplication indicate that &#8288;




Z



{\displaystyle \mathbb {Z} }

&#8288; under multiplication forms a [commutative monoid](/Commutative_monoid). However, it's crucial to note that not every integer possesses a multiplicative inverse (for instance, the number 2 has no integer inverse that, when multiplied, yields 1). This absence of universal multiplicative inverses means that &#8288;




Z



{\displaystyle \mathbb {Z} }

&#8288; under multiplication, despite its other virtues, does *not* constitute a [group](/Group_(mathematics)).

When all the rules from the preceding property table (with the exception of the very last one) are considered in their entirety, they collectively declare that &#8288;




Z



{\displaystyle \mathbb {Z} }

&#8288;, endowed with both addition and multiplication, forms a [commutative ring](/Commutative_ring) with [unity](/Multiplicative_identity). It stands as the quintessential prototype for all mathematical objects possessing such an [algebraic structure](/Algebraic_structure). Only those [equalities](/Equality_(mathematics)) of [expressions](/Algebraic_expression) that hold true in &#8288;




Z



{\displaystyle \mathbb {Z} }

&#8288; [for all](/For_all) possible values of variables are also true in any unital [commutative ring](/Commutative_ring). It's worth remembering that certain non-zero integers may, under specific mappings, correspond to the [additive identity](/Additive_identity) (zero) in certain other [rings](/Ring_(mathematics)).

The absence of [zero divisors](/Zero_divisor) within the integers (as noted in the final property in the table) signifies that the [commutative ring](/Commutative_ring) &#8288;




Z



{\displaystyle \mathbb {Z} }

&#8288; is, in fact, an [integral domain](/Integral_domain). This is a desirable quality, implying a certain 'integrity' in its multiplicative structure.

The aforementioned lack of multiplicative inverses, which is simply another way of stating that &#8288;




Z



{\displaystyle \mathbb {Z} }

&#8288; is not [closed](/Closure_(mathematics)) under division, explicitly means that &#8288;




Z



{\displaystyle \mathbb {Z} }

&#8288; does not qualify as a [field](/Field_(mathematics)). The smallest [field](/Field_(mathematics)) that comprehensively contains the integers as a [subring](/Subring) is the [field of rational numbers](/Rational_number). The elegant process by which the [rational numbers](/Rational_number) are constructed from the integers can be analogously applied to form the [field of fractions](/Field_of_fractions) for any given [integral domain](/Integral_domain). Conversely, one can embark from an [algebraic number field](/Algebraic_number_field) (which is essentially an extension of [rational numbers](/Rational_number)) and systematically extract its specific [ring of integers](/Ring_of_integers), a structure that, predictably, includes &#8288;




Z



{\displaystyle \mathbb {Z} }

&#8288; as its inherent [subring](/Subring).

While standard division, as a binary operation yielding a single result, is not universally defined over &#8288;




Z



{\displaystyle \mathbb {Z} }

&#8288;, a more nuanced form of division—"division with remainder"—is indeed well-defined. This is formally known as [Euclidean division](/Euclidean_division), and it possesses a remarkably important property: given any two integers, *a* and *b*, where *b* is emphatically not [zero](/0), there exist a unique pair of integers, *q* (the quotient) and *r* (the [remainder](/Remainder)), such that the equation *a* = *q* × *b* + *r* holds true, and the [remainder](/Remainder) *r* satisfies the condition 0 ≤ *r* < |*b*|, where |*b*| signifies the [absolute value](/Absolute_value) of *b*. This elegant principle forms the bedrock of the [Euclidean algorithm](/Euclidean_algorithm), a venerable method for efficiently computing [greatest common divisors](/Greatest_common_divisor) through a precise sequence of [Euclidean divisions](/Euclidean_division).

These properties reveal that &#8288;




Z



{\displaystyle \mathbb {Z} }

&#8288; is, in mathematical parlance, a [Euclidean domain](/Euclidean_domain). This designation carries significant implications, as it inherently implies that &#8288;




Z



{\displaystyle \mathbb {Z} }

&#8288; is also a [principal ideal domain](/Principal_ideal_domain). Consequently, this means that any positive integer can be uniquely expressed as a product of [primes](/Prime_number) in an [essentially unique](/Essentially_unique) manner, disregarding the order of the prime factors and their signs. This profound insight is formally enshrined as the [fundamental theorem of arithmetic](/Fundamental_theorem_of_arithmetic), a cornerstone of number theory.

## Order-theoretic properties

The set &#8288;




Z



{\displaystyle \mathbb {Z} }

&#8288; is characterized as a [totally ordered set](/Total_order), meaning that for any two distinct integers, one is always demonstrably greater or smaller than the other. Furthermore, this set exists without an [upper or lower bound](/Upper_and_lower_bounds); it extends infinitely in both positive and negative directions. The inherent ordering of &#8288;




Z



{\displaystyle \mathbb {Z} }

&#8288; is universally understood and given by the familiar sequence:
:... −3 < −2 < −1 < 0 < 1 < 2 < 3 < ....
An integer is unambiguously defined as positive if its value is greater than [zero](/0), and negative if its value is less than [zero](/0). The number [zero](/0) itself holds a neutral position, being explicitly defined as neither negative nor positive. It simply *is*.

This inherent ordering of integers is, quite conveniently, perfectly compatible with the standard algebraic operations, in the following manner:

*   If *a* < *b* and *c* < *d*, then it logically follows that *a* + *c* < *b* + *d*. The sums maintain the inequality.
*   If *a* < *b* and 0 < *c* (meaning *c* is a positive integer), then *ac* < *bc*. Multiplication by a positive integer preserves the inequality.

Thus, it is definitively established that &#8288;




Z



{\displaystyle \mathbb {Z} }

&#8288;, when considered in conjunction with its inherent ordering, forms an [ordered ring](/Ordered_ring).

The integers hold a singular distinction as the *only* nontrivial [totally ordered](/Totally_ordered) [abelian group](/Abelian_group) whose positive elements exhibit the property of being [well-ordered](/Well-ordered). This rather technical statement is, intriguingly, mathematically equivalent to the assertion that any [Noetherian](/Noetherian_ring) [valuation ring](/Valuation_ring) is either a [field](/Field_(mathematics)) (a structure where every non-zero element has a multiplicative inverse) or, more specifically, a [discrete valuation ring](/Discrete_valuation_ring). A subtle but crucial point for those who appreciate such nuances.

